SIMPLE: of
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Of
<hw>Of</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧v)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>of</ets>
of, from, off; akin to D. & OS. <ets>af</ets>, G. <ets>ab</ets> off,
OHG. <ets>aba</ets> from, away, Icel., Dan., Sw., & Goth. <ets>af</ets>,
L. <ets>ab</ets>, Gr. <?/, Skr. <ets>apa</ets>. Cf. <er>Off</er>,
<er>A-</er> (2), <er>Ab-</er>, <er>After</er>, <er>Epi-</er>.]</ety>
<def>In a general sense, from, or out from; proceeding from; belonging
to; relating to; concerning; -- used in a variety of applications;
as:</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Denoting that from which anything proceeds;
indicating origin, source, descent, and the like; <as>as, he is
<ex>of</ex> a race of kings; he is <ex>of</ex> noble
blood.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That holy thing which shall be born <qex>of</qex> thee shall be
called the Son of God.</q> <rj><qau>Luke i. 35.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have received <qex>of</qex> the Lord that which also I delivered
unto you.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. xi. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Denoting possession or ownership, or the relation of
subject to attribute; <as>as, the apartment <ex>of</ex> the consul: the
power <ex>of</ex> the king; a man <ex>of</ex> courage; the gate <ex>of
heaven</ex>.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Poor <xex>of</xex> spirit.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Denoting the material of which anything is composed,
or that which it contains; <as>as, a throne <ex>of</ex> gold; a sword
<ex>of</ex> steel; a wreath <ex>of</ex> mist; a cup <ex>of</ex>
water.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Denoting part of an aggregate or whole; belonging to
a number or quantity mentioned; out of; from amongst; <as>as,
<ex>of</ex> this little he had some to spare; some <ex>of</ex> the mines
were unproductive; most <ex>of</ex> the company.</as></def><-- =
partative genitive -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is <qex>of</qex> the Lord's mercies that we are not
consumed.</q> <rj><qau>Lam. iii. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a duty to communicate <qex>of</qex> those blessings we have
received.</q> <rj><qau>Franklin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Denoting that by which a person or thing is actuated
or impelled; also, the source of a purpose or action; due to; <as>as,
they went <ex>of</ex> their own will; no body can move <ex>of</ex>
itself; he did it <ex>of</ex> necessity.</as></def><-- = out of, from,
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For it was <qex>of</qex> the Lord to harden their hearts.</q>
<rj><qau>Josh. xi. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Denoting reference to a thing; about; concerning;
relating to; <as>as, to boast <ex>of</ex> one's achievements; they
talked <ex>of</ex> many things</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Knew you <qex>of</qex> this fair work?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Denoting nearness or distance, either in space or
time; from; <as>as, within a league <ex>of</ex> the town; within an hour
<ex>of</ex> the appointed time.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Denoting identity or equivalence; -- used with a
name or appellation, and equivalent to the relation of apposition;
<as>as, the continent <ex>of</ex> America; the city <ex>of</ex> Rome;
the Island <ex>of</ex> Cuba.</as></def><-- always preceded by a type
name? -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Denoting the agent, or person by whom, or thing by
which, anything is, or is done; by.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And told to her <qex>of</qex> [by] some.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He taught in their synagogues, being glorified <qex>of</qex>
all.</q> <rj><qau>Luke iv. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Jesus] being forty days tempted <qex>of</qex> the devil.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke iv. 1, 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The use of the word in this sense, as applied to
persons, is nearly obsolete.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Denoting relation to place or time; belonging to,
or connected with; <as>as, men <ex>of</ex> Athens; the people
<ex>of</ex> the Middle Ages; in the days <ex>of</ex>
Herod.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Denoting passage from one state to another;
from.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧O miserable <xex>of</xex>
happy.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>During; in the course of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not be seen to wink <qex>of</qex> all the day.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My custom always <qex>of</qex> the afternoon.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Of</xex> may be used in a subjective or an
objective sense. ⟦ldquo⟧The love <xex>of</xex> God⟦rdquo⟧ may mean, our
love for God, or God's love for us.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>From</xex> is the primary sense of this
preposition; a sense retained in <xex>off</xex>, the same word
differently written for distinction. But this radical sense disappears
in most of its application; as, a man <xex>of</xex> genius; a man
<xex>of</xex> rare endowments; a fossil <xex>of</xex> a red color, or
<xex>of</xex> an hexagonal figure; he lost all hope <xex>of</xex>
relief; an affair <xex>of</xex> the cabinet; he is a man <xex>of</xex>
decayed fortune; what is the price <xex>of</xex> corn? In these and
similar phrases, <xex>of</xex> denotes property or possession, or a
relation of some sort involving connection. These applications, however
all proceeded from the same primary sense. That which proceeds from, or
is produced by, a person or thing, either has had, or still has, a close
connection with the same; and hence the word was applied to cases of
mere connection, not involving at all the idea of separation.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Of consequence</b></col>, <cd>of importance, value, or
influence.</cd> -- <col><b>Of late</b></col>, <cd>recently; in time not
long past.</cd> -- <col><b>Of old</b></col>, <cd>formerly; in time long
past.</cd> -- <col><b>Of one's self</b></col>, <cd>by one's self;
without help or prompting; spontaneously.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why, knows not Montague, that <qex>of</qex> itself⟦br⟧
England is safe, if true within itself?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Off</ent>⟦br⟧
